chatgpt_double_star.new_statement: Abortion law should aim to protect human well-being in a way that people with different moral convictions can live with: keep early, time‑sensitive decisions in the confidential care of patients and licensed clinicians, and require that any regulations be medically justified, workable in practice, and free of criminal penalties for patients. If limits are adopted, they should be clear and include real-world exceptions for serious threats to health, pregnancies from violence, and severe fetal anomalies, while allowing clinicians’ conscience accommodations when they do not block timely care. A durable compromise also commits public resources to reduce unplanned pregnancy and hardship—accurate education, affordable contraception, prenatal and mental-health care, paid leave, childcare, and adoption support—so fewer people face crisis decisions in the first place.
